A colony of Genoese⁷⁶, which had been planted at Phocaea ⁷¹ on the Ionian coast, was enriched by the lucrative mo- nopoly of alum ⁷³ ; and their tranquillity, under the Turkiss1 empire, was secured by the annual payment of tribute. In the last civil war of the ottonum, the Genoese governor, Adorno, a bold and ambi- tious youth, embraced the party of Amurath ; and undertook with seven stout gallies to transport him from Afia to Europe. The sultan and five hundred guards embarked on board the admiral’s ship3 which was manned by eight hundred of the bravest Franks.
